data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire manual `Expression.Lambda`/`Expression.Call` construction no longer compiles. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
// EF Core 10
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No expression tree plumbing needed — conditional logic works directly inside the lambda body.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — uniquified and full-path prefixed

Two changes combine here:

- **Shared property names** (e.g., `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street`) now get a numeric suffix to disambiguate, potentially renaming columns.
- **Nested complex types** now use full path: `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City` (was `BillingAddress_City`).

Both generate schema-altering migrations. **Fix:** pin the old column names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
    {
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
    {
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
        {
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

All methods (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) gained a `string logCommandText` parameter. Your implementation won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection, DbCommand command,
        DbContext context, Guid commandId, Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)          // ← new parameter (redacted SQL)
    { /* logging — use logCommandText for safe log output */ }
}
```

`logCommandText` contains redacted SQL (constants may be replaced); use `command.CommandText` for actual SQL. Update **every** method on the interface — they all received the same new parameter.
